# Chapter 5 — The fifteen record types

Fifteen slat-record types ship in the SLAT 1.0 registry. Each one has
a job in a real Lacuna system. When the runtime sees one of these
records, it auto-rehydrates to a native object with the right
builder.

Consumers can invent their own types on top of these. Nothing forces
you into the list. But these are the fifteen the running system
already understands.

I'll walk each one with a working example. Read them at your own pace.

## 1. `atom` — training-corpus atom

the runtime's training corpus is atoms. Each atom is a labeled fragment of
teaching material: a Scheme snippet, an incident narrative, a
correction pair, a domain fact.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(atom
  :id \\\"atm-scheme-lambda-001\\\"
  :type 'code
  :domain 'scheme
  :weight 1.0
  :body (lambda (x) (* x x))
  :meta (:tags ('language 'lambda 'basics)
         :author 'motoi
         :audited-by 'zain))\")
```

When Forge streams this in during a training run, it reads with
`slat-read`, gets a rehydrated `Atom` object, checks the `:weight`
field to decide how many times to feed the pair, and moves on.

**Without atom as a native type:** the corpus reader parses JSON with
a `_type: \"atom\"` sentinel, and every consumer has to remember to
check that sentinel. Miss it, and the weight isn't respected, and
training loss diverges silently.

## 2. `event` — log or bus entry

The workhorse. `card.opened`, `mood.changed`, `cortex.slice.updated`,
`training.iter.completed`. Millions per day, streaming through Loam.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(event :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
       :kind \\\"card.opened\\\"
       :id 'welcome
       :by 'motoi
       :surface 'desktop)\")
```

Loam ingests these into projections (`SYSTEM/cortex-subscription-drift`,
`SAKURA/mood-history`). Each projection is itself a stream of slat
records. The whole observability spine speaks one language.

## 3. `message` — cross-process message

The mailbox format. Foreman-to-worker, worker-to-worker,
artifact-service-to-artifact-service.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(message :v 1
         :from 'foreman
         :to 'worker/mlx-1
         :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
         :detail (start-training-run
                  :seed 4137
                  :adapters \\\"adapters.safetensors\\\"
                  :max-iter 68520))\")
```

The `:detail` field carries another slat-record. Recursion is native.
Chapter 13 walks the mailbox lifecycle in detail.

## 4. `record` — generic keyed record

The catch-all. When nothing else fits, use `record`.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(record :author 'motoi
        :ts     #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
        :note   \\\"I remembered the paddle game today.\\\")\")
```

Useful for one-offs where a full type feels heavy. The runtime treats
it as a bag of keys.

## 5. `snapshot` — point-in-time state dump

Cortex writes snapshots when something crosses a threshold worth
remembering.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(snapshot :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
          :subject 'motoi.mood
          :body (mood :valence 0.6 :arousal 0.4 :confidence 0.82))\")
```

Snapshots let you say \"what did she feel like at 6:22?\" They're the
frames of a stop-motion film.

## 6. `delta` — change between two snapshots

The other half of the same story.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(delta :from-ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:15:00Z\\\"
       :to-ts   #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
       :changes ((valence 0.5 -> 0.6)
                 (arousal 0.5 -> 0.4)))\")
```

Deltas let you say \"how did she change?\" Together with snapshots, you
get the timeline.

## 7. `index` — lookup table

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(index :key 'atom-id
       :type 'trie
       :entries ((atm-001 \\\"carts/basics/car-cdr.sks\\\")
                 (atm-002 \\\"carts/basics/lambda.sks\\\")))\")
```

Indexes let you look up records by key. Atom retrieval, corpus
navigation, artifact-catalog. When the index is small enough to fit
in RAM, one of these covers it.

## 8. `log` — structured log line

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(log :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\"
     :level :warn
     :module 'training
     :body \\\"warmup pike detected at iter 350\\\")\")
```

Loam ingests `.slatl` files of log records. Every line is one log
entry. Every entry has structured fields. No regex parsing. No format
strings to guess.

## 9. `transcript` — chat or conversation

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(transcript
  :messages ((user \\\"hi motoi\\\")
             (motoi \\\"hi. what would you like to build?\\\")
             (user \\\"a small game\\\")
             (motoi \\\"paddle and ball? that's a good first game.\\\")))\")
```

The `:messages` field is a list of `(role text)` pairs. Correction
pairs, dialogues, training conversations — all use this shape.

## 10. `corpus-pair` — paired training example

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(corpus-pair
  :prompt \\\"what does (car '(1 2 3)) return?\\\"
  :completion \\\"1 — the first element of the list.\\\"
  :weight 1.0
  :provenance 'motoi-scheme-book-ch04)\")
```

The training loop reads a corpus of these. `:weight` says how many
times to feed the pair. `:provenance` says where the pair came from.

## 11. `spec` — machine-readable spec fragment

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(spec :id 'inferred/weather-observation
      :kind 'record
      :required (:temp :humidity)
      :optional (:pressure :station)
      :positional ())\")
```

Auto-assembly (Chapter 11) uses `spec` records to describe inferred
shapes. Consumers can register them to get automatic rehydration.

## 12. `test-vector` — reader/writer fixture

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(test-vector
  :name \\\"nested-record-with-instant\\\"
  :input \\\"(event :ts #inst \\\\\\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\\\\\" :kind \\\\\\\"card.opened\\\\\\\")\\\"
  :expected (event :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\" :kind \\\"card.opened\\\"))\")
```

Every binding runs the shared fixture set. If JavaScript and Python
disagree on any test-vector, CI blocks the merge.

## 13. `artifact-state` — serialized artifact instance

Every artifact in the running system serializes as one of these.
Chat, IDE, RAG, animation, game — all the same shape.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(artifact-state
  :type 'chat
  :id \\\"chat-2026-07-11-alfred\\\"
  :state ((messages ((user \\\"hi\\\") (motoi \\\"hi\\\")))
          (mood     (mood :valence 0.6 :arousal 0.4))
          (draft    \\\"i was going to ask about...\\\")))\")
```

The runtime opens an artifact by writing an `artifact-state` slat. Closes
it by reading the slat back later.

## 14. `cortex-slice` — a piece of the runtime's memory

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(cortex-slice
  :key 'kid.alfred.programs
  :value ((paddle-game :cart-id \\\"cart-1234\\\" :last-touched 12))
  :owner 'motoi
  :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T18:22:00Z\\\")\")
```

The cortex is the runtime's memory. It's slats. Chapter 14 walks the whole
memory system.

## 15. `incident-narrative` — a lesson learned

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"
(incident-narrative
  :id \\\"in-warmup-pike-350\\\"
  :incident (event :ts #inst \\\"2026-07-11T04:00:00Z\\\"
                   :kind 'val-loss-divergence :at-iter 350)
  :philosopher 'zain
  :messages ((zain \\\"val loss went up at 350; train loss stayed flat.\\\")
             (motoi \\\"is that a warmup pike or a real divergence?\\\")
             (zain \\\"the trend line matters more than the spot. watch iter 2000.\\\"))
  :lesson \\\"Watch the val curve, not the train curve.\\\"
  :atom-refs (atm-training-005 atm-training-008))\")
```

Incident narratives are how the runtime learns from what happened. Chapter
15 in the Book of Reason walks the shape. The atoms it references are
the ones the training loop plays back when the same shape shows up
again.

## Consumer-invented types

Anyone can invent a new head symbol without asking. If you write:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(weather-observation :temp 72.4 :humidity 0.63)\")
```

...the runtime returns a generic record with `_form: weather-observation`
and the two keys. Not an error. Just a record the runtime doesn't have
a native builder for.

Later, if you register a builder (Chapter 11), those records
auto-rehydrate to native `WeatherObservation` objects. Old records
still work. New records get typed. No coordinated language change.

## Try this

Write a `record` slat that describes something you did today. Read it
back. Change one field. Read it again.

```motoi-scheme
(define today
  (slat-read \"
(record :date #inst \\\"2026-07-12T00:00:00Z\\\"
        :did  \\\"read the book of slat\\\"
        :next \\\"try building a small cart\\\")\"))

(slat-key today 'did)
```

You get back your string. That's the substrate at work — you wrote a
record, read it back, pulled a field out, moved on.

## Where next

Chapter 6 walks the two file framings — `.slat` for whole-document
records, `.slatl` for line-delimited streams. Same grammar, different
strategies.

Chapters 7 through 10 walk the reader and writer, then
canonicalization, content-addressing, and signing — the four
mechanical concepts that turn \"we agreed on a shape\" into \"we agreed
on a shape and we can prove nobody changed it.\"

